{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181018123213|864623465","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Seth_Moulton","to":"Seth Moulton"}],"pages":{"43714153":{"pageid":43714153,"ns":0,"title":"Seth Moulton","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-19T15:10:38Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Seth Moulton\n| image = Seth Moulton.jpg\n| state = [[Massachusetts]]\n| district = {{ushr|MA|6|6th}}\n| term_start = January 3, 2015\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[John F. Tierney]]\n| successor = \n| birth_name = Seth Wilbur Moulton\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|10|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Salem, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Liz Boardman Moulton\n| children = 1\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| education = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]], [[Master of Public Policy|MPP]])\n| website = {{url|moulton.house.gov|House website}}\n| allegiance = {{flag|United States}}\n| branch = {{flag|United States Marine Corps}}\n| serviceyears = 2001\u20132008\n| rank = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n| battles = [[Iraq War]]\n| mawards = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|20px|border]] [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] (2) with [[\"V\" Device|Combat \"V\"]]<br>[[File:Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]] with Combat \"V\"\n}}\n'''Seth Wilbur Moulton''' (born October 24, 1978) is an American politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district]] since 2015. A former [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] [[Military Officer|officer]], he is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard University]] in 2001 with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[physics]], Moulton joined the [[United States Marine Corps]]. He served four tours in [[Iraq War|Iraq]] and then went on to earn his [[master's degree]]s in [[Master of Business Administration|business]] and [[Master of Public Policy|public policy]] in a [[Double degree|dual program]] at Harvard. He entered politics in 2014, running for Massachusetts's 6th congressional district. He defeated incumbent U.S. Representative [[John F. Tierney]] in the Democratic primary and then defeated former Republican State Senator [[Richard Tisei]] in the general election.\n\n==Early life, education, and commission==\nSeth Wilbur Moulton was born on October 24, 1978, in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], the son of Lynn Alice (n\u00e9e Meader), a secretary, and Wilbur Thomas Moulton, Jr., a real estate attorney.<ref name=madepeace/><ref>{{cite web|title=0695. Lynn Alice Meade|url=http://www.themeaderfamily.org/test/showPage.php?ID=0695 |publisher=Meader Family Organization|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gomes|first1=Peter J.|title=The Good Life: Truths That Last in Times of Need|date=2003|publisher=HarperOne|page=365|url=http://librarum.org/book/24442/365|accessdate=November 6, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106043435/http://librarum.org/book/24442/365|archivedate=November 6, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Moulton grew up in [[Marblehead, Massachusetts]], as the oldest of three siblings.<ref name=madepeace>{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/2008/01/how-the-moultons-made-peace-with-the-war|title=How the Moultons Made Peace with the War|work=[[Boston Magazine]]|author=Phyllis Karas |date=February 2008}}</ref> He graduated from [[Phillips Academy]], a co-educational boarding and day [[university-preparatory school]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andover.edu/calendar/pages/moultontalk2014.aspx|work=[[Phillips Academy]]|title=Seth Moulton '97 talks about service on April 22}}</ref> and attended [[Harvard University]], where he earned his [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[physics]] in 2001. He gave the Undergraduate English Oration at his [[graduation|commencement]], focusing on the importance of service.<ref name=warprofiles>{{cite news|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2003/6/5/war-profiles-seth-w-moulton-01|title=War Profiles: Seth W. Moulton '01, 2nd Lieutenant, U.S. Marine Corps|work=[[Harvard Crimson]]|date=June 5, 2003}}</ref> \n\nMoulton joined the Marine Corps after graduation, a few months before the [[September 11 attacks]],<ref name=disillusioned>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/09/us/politics/disillusioned-in-iraq-but-prodded-to-serve-again.html|title=Disillusioned in Iraq, but Prodded to Serve Again|work=[[New York Times]] |author=Jeremy W. Peters|date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> and attended the [[Officer Candidate School]] in [[Quantico, Virginia]]. After graduating in 2002 with the rank of [[second lieutenant]], Moulton was among the first service members to enter [[Baghdad]] at the beginning of the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=madepeace/><ref name=warprofiles/>\n\n==Military career==\nDuring the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], Moulton led one of the first infantry platoons to enter [[Baghdad]]. He served a total of four tours of duty in [[Iraq]] from 2003 to 2008.<ref name=madepeace/> Moulton took part in the 2003 [[Battle of Nasiriyah]], leading a platoon that cleared a hostile stronghold. In that action, he went to the aid of a Marine wounded by friendly fire, and for his actions he was awarded the [[Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]] for valor.<ref name=underplays>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/10/17/moulton-underplays-military-service/lY9FfmOrviwL2LAFHr61dO/story.html|title=Seth Moulton underplays military service|first=Walter V. |last=Robinson |date=October 18, 2014|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Moulton was active in combat against insurgent forces in Iraq, including the 2004 [[Battle of Najaf (2004)|Battle of Najaf]] against the militia of [[Muqtada al-Sadr]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/now/shows/316/No-End-in-Sight.html|work=[[PBS]]|date=April 20, 2007|title=Director's Interview: Charles Ferguson}}</ref> Over two days, he \"fearlessly exposed himself to enemy fire\" as his platoon was pinned down under heavy fire and then directed the supporting fire that repelled the attack. He received the [[Bronze Star Medal]] for his actions in this battle.<ref name=underplays/>\n\nHe told only his campaign manager, a former Marine, about these awards, keeping them secret even from his parents. When ''[[Boston Globe]]'' reporter [[Walter V. Robinson]] disclosed in October 2014 that Moulton had earned the Bronze Star and the Commendation Medal, Moulton said that \"[t]here is a healthy disrespect among veterans who served on the front lines for people who walk around telling war stories\". He said he was uncomfortable calling attention to his own awards out of respect to \"many others who did heroic things and received no awards at all.\" He asked Robinson not to refer to him as a hero: \"Look, we served our country, and we served the guys next to us. And it's not something to brag about.\" The ''Globe'' reported that \"his voice choked with emotion\" as he added: \"The greatest honor of my life was to lead these men in my platoon, even though it was a war that I and they disagreed with.\"<ref name=underplays/>\n\nIn 2008, General [[David Petraeus]] requested that Moulton be assigned to work as a special liaison with tribal leaders in Southern Iraq during his fourth tour of duty in Iraq. Following that tour, Moulton was discharged from the Marine Corps with the rank of captain.<ref name=madepeace/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.phillipian.net/articles/2014/09/11/seth-moulton-97-wins-democratic-party-primary|title=Seth Moulton '97 Wins The Democratic Party Primary|first=Kailash|last=Sundaram|date=September 12, 2014|work=[[Phillips Academy]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009220610/http://www.phillipian.net/articles/2014/09/11/seth-moulton-97-wins-democratic-party-primary|archivedate=October 9, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/05/11/marine-veteran-seth-moulton-wages-insurgent-campaign-against-fellow-democrat-john-tierney/3RdZyq5hE0o8QicDcNGVQO/story.html |title=Marine Veteran Seth Moulton Wages Insurgent Campaign Against Fellow Democrat John Tierney|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=May 11, 2014 |first=Stephanie|last=Ebbert|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Media contributions===\nIn 2003, Moulton co-hosted a television program with his Iraqi interpreter, Mohammed Harba, called \"Moulton and Mohammed,\" during which they discussed regional conditions in the period following the U.S. invasion before an audience of U.S. servicemen and Iraqi citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weekendamerica.publicradio.org/programs/2007/01/06/moulton_amp_mohammed.html|title=Moulton & Mohammed|work=[[American Public Media]]|date=January 6, 2007|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140924072653/http://weekendamerica.publicradio.org/programs/2007/01/06/moulton_amp_mohammed.html|archivedate=September 24, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The show ended after three months when Moulton's unit left the area.<ref name=madepeace/>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2008, Moulton was frequently interviewed about his experiences as an officer in Iraq by U.S. national media, including [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]], and [[National Public Radio|NPR]] programs ''[[Morning Edition]]'' and ''[[All Things Considered]]''.<ref name=madepeace/><ref name=\"NPR interviews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/search/index.php?searchinput=seth+moulton|title=Search Results:Seth Moulton}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = And are you telling me that's the best America can do? No. Don't tell me that, don't tell the Marines who fought for a month in [[Najaf]] that, don't tell the marines who are still fighting every day in [[Fallujah]] that that's the best America can do... That makes me angry.|source= \u2014 [[No End in Sight]], ''Seth Moulton''|width=50%|align=right}}\n\nMoulton was also prominently featured in the [[Academy Award]]-nominated 2007 documentary ''[[No End in Sight]]''. In the film, Moulton criticized the U.S. government's handling of the [[History of Iraq (2003\u201311)|occupation of Iraq]]. [[UCLA]] anthropology professor [[Sherry Ortner]] wrote that Moulton's comments \"sum[med] up the emotional tone of the film.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ortner |first1=Sherry B.|title=Not Hollywood: Independent Film at the Twilight of the American Dream|date=2013|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0822354260 |page=245 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIqdEw2VToUC&pg=PA245|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Private sector career==\nFollowing his return from active duty with the Marines in 2008, Moulton attended a dual-degree program at the [[Harvard Business School]] and the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]], receiving [[master's degree]]s in [[Master of Business Administration|business]] and [[public policy]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Sullivan Jim|title=Tierney faces Democratic challenger for his seat|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/07/06/representative-john-tierney-facing-primary-challenge-from-within-his-own-democratic-party-byfellow-democrat-marine-seth-moulton/MezmoWMuXBlnh28g3zIPxL/story.html|accessdate=September 13, 2014|work=Boston Globe|date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> After graduate school, Moulton worked for one year as managing director of the [[Texas Central Railway]], a transportation firm that is in the process of building a [[high-speed rail]] connection between [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] and [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]], [[Texas]].<ref name=globeedit>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/editorials/2014/09/01/democratic-primary-endorsement-seth-moulton-for-congress/LAmkYNWsDafuuleivth96L/story.html|title=Seth Moulton For Congress|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Moulton and a graduate school classmate founded Eastern Healthcare Partners, a small business that Moulton has invoked to show he was a \"successful entrepreneur\" who understands \"what it's like to face that day when you might not meet payroll.\" The company raised investor funds and drafted a partnership agreement with [[Johns Hopkins School of Medicine]], but in October 2014 the ''Boston Globe'' reported that by the time Moulton ran for Congress, EHP had no revenue, was still incubating, and had closed its only Massachusetts office.[https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/10/23/small-businesses-are-sometimes-really-small/Xg1p3vOuopiBU8TUDHFlEO/story.html]\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n====2012 speculation====\nMoulton had considered running against Democratic Representative [[John F. Tierney]] of [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district]] as an Independent in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2012#District 6|2012 elections]], but he decided against it in July 2012, saying that \"the time and the logistics of putting together all the campaign infrastructure, organizing the volunteers ... the fundraising\u2014it's just too much to accomplish in three months.\" Had he run and been elected, he would have caucused with the Democrats. He told ''Roll Call'' that his own polling \"showed there was in fact a clear path to victory\" and said he might run for office in the future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Massachusetts: Independent Seth Moulton Will Not Run |url=http://atr.rollcall.com/massachusetts-independent-seth-moulton-will-not-run|accessdate=October 8, 2014|work=Roll Call|date=July 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2014 election====\nOn July 8, 2013, Moulton announced his candidacy in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2014#District 6|2014 congressional race]] for [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district|Massachusetts' 6th district]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Moulton Launches Tierney Challenge|url=http://www.lowellsun.com/news/ci_23632217/moulton-launches-tierney-challenge |first=Katie|last=Lannan|accessdate=October 25, 2014|work=Lowell Sun|date=July 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe race had been recognized for its competitiveness by national and regional media throughout the election cycle.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/the-daily-rundown/the-39-democrats-who-broke-ranks-obama |title=The 39 Democrats who broke ranks from Obama|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|date= November 15, 2013|accessdate=November 11, 2014|first=Jessica|last=Taylor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/01/politics/2014-house-races/index.html |title=5 House Races to Watch in 2014| publisher= [[CNN]] |date= January 1, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014|first1=Leigh Ann|last1= Caldwell |first2= Paul|last2= Steinhauser}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/rothenblog/top-5-races-to-watch-in-new-england-2/?dcz= |title=Top 5 Races to Watch in New England| first=Nathan L.|last=Gonzales |work=[[Roll Call]]|date= August 21, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=battle>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3204263/a-battle-of-two-veterans/ |title=A Battle of Two Veterans |first=Joe |last=Klein |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= August 28, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/iraq-vet-gives-tierney-tough-challenge-in-massachusetts/article/2552774 |title=Iraq vet gives Tierney tough challenge in Massachusetts| work=Washington Examiner |date=September 3, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014|first=Betsy|last=Woodruff}}</ref> Moulton challenged Tierney in the Democratic [[primary election|primary]]. According to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine political columnist [[Joe Klein]], Moulton \"refused to distinguish himself from Tierney on most issues. He's running on freshness and dynamism.\"<ref name=battle/> The ''Boston Globe'' editorial board wrote: \"Moulton and Tierney share nearly identical political views, but Moulton's background, and his approach to discussing the issues, suggests an openness to new perspectives.\"<ref name=globeedit/>\n\nTierney's campaign claimed in campaign advertisements that Moulton received campaign contributions from a [[New Hampshire]] [[political action committee]] that previously donated only to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]], implying that Moulton must hold conservative views.<ref name=attack>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/09/02/john-tierney-launches-attack-against-democratic-challenger/TY8shjpb0yq4sIvu00S1DN/story.html |title=John Tierney Launches Attack Against Democratic Challenger|work= Boston Globe |date= September 2, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref> Moulton denied being more conservative than his opponent,<ref name=Iraqvote>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2014/08/17/seth-moulton-puts-john-tierney-iraq-vote-back-play/E9o1a9BVuihUzgkggu0zKO/story.html |title=Seth Moulton puts John Tierney's Iraq vote back in play |work=Boston Globe |date= August 8, 2014 |accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref> and stated that the Republican PAC donation was returned. Public [[Federal Election Commission]] filings confirmed that the donation was returned in February 2014.<ref name=attack/>\n\nMoulton said that he opposed the Iraq War in which he served. A Tierney campaign staff member said that Moulton had \"changed his mind\" and highlighted Tierney's vote in Congress to oppose [[Iraq Resolution|the 2002 resolution authorizing the U.S. Invasion of Iraq]].<ref name=Iraqvote/> Moulton also received the first-ever political endorsement from [[Stanley McChrystal|Ret. Gen. Stanley McChrystal]] during the campaign.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/08/04/former-gen-stanley-mcchrystal-endorse-congressional-hopeful-seth-moulton/fRb3G9dh9Soue7CWfOSKpJ/story.html \"Retired Gen. McChrystal endorses congress hopeful Moulton\" by Joshua Miller, ''Boston Globe'', August 4, 2014]</ref>\n\nMoulton defeated Tierney in the primary with 50.8% of the vote to Tierney's 40.1%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Massachusetts Election Statistics |url=http://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/search/year_from:2014/year_to:2014/stage:Primaries|website=Massachusetts Election Division|accessdate=October 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoulton was endorsed by Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Elizabeth Warren endorses Seth Moulton for Congress|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/09/27/sen-warren-endorses-moulton-for-congress/WWJckEXXGYU8PyFTSCaqiJ/story.html|accessdate=October 14, 2014|agency=Associated Press| work=Boston Globe|date=September 28, 2014}}</ref> for the general election. In October 2014, he withdrew from a debate sponsored by radio station [[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]] because of a series of New York fundraisers, where he welcomed Democratic National Committee Chairwoman [[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stout |first1=Matt|title=Richard Tisei rips Seth Moulton cash grab in 6th |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/local_politics/2014/10/richard_tisei_rips_seth_moulton_cash_grab_in_6th|accessdate=October 14, 2014|work=Boston Herald|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> The campaigns of Moulton and his Republican opponent, [[Richard Tisei]], were held up as an example of how candidates can compete with respect for each other.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle|first1=Jason|title=This Massachusetts Race Will Restore Your Faith in Our Democracy |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120109/tisei-moulton-race-mass-rare-choice-two-great-candidates |accessdate=November 5, 2014|work=New Republic|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoulton defeated Tisei in the general election.\n\n====2016 election====\nMoulton was uncontested for reelection in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/massachusetts-house-district-6 |title=Massachusetts U.S. House 6th District Results: Seth Moulton Wins |date=December 13, 2016 |website=nytimes.com |publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger Jr.]] |access-date=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2020 speculation ====\nMoulton has been mentioned as a possible candidate for President.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/05/01/seth-moulton-creating-buzz-about-presidential-bid/zxAxmueS0cnwGmfeK1hxwO/story.html |title=Speculation is stirring about a Seth Moulton presidential bid |first=Jim |last=O'Sullivan |date=May 2, 2017 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mahaskey |first=M. Scott |url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/07/28/seth-moulton-congressman-run-president-2020-profile-215428 |title=Generals Love Him, Top Democrats Despise Him. Can Seth Moulton Be President Anyway? |work=Politico Magazine}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nMoulton was sworn into the [[114th United States Congress]] on January 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/representative-sworn-into-office|title=Congressman Seth Moulton Sworn-in to 114th Congress|accessdate=January 6, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122052354/https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/representative-sworn-into-office|archivedate=January 22, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n{{U.S. Congress committee assignments\n |congress=114\n |ref=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-moulton-named-house-budget-committee|title=CONGRESSMAN MOULTON NAMED TO HOUSE BUDGET COMMITTEE|accessdate=January 21, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122052635/https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-moulton-named-house-budget-committee|archivedate=January 22, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-seth-moulton-named-house-armed-services-committee|title=CONGRESSMAN MOULTON NAMED TO HOUSE ARMED SERVICES COMMITTEE|accessdate=January 9, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122060710/https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-seth-moulton-named-house-armed-services-committee|archivedate=January 22, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n |committees=\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Small Business]]'''\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Health and Technology|Health and Technology]] (Ranking Member)\n}}\nMoulton is a member of the [[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=21 March 2018}}</ref> and the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=|publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nIn Moulton's campaign advertisements, he has called himself a \"progressive Democrat\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Seth Moulton said he smoked Pot at Harvard, supports legalization |url=http://www.nobomagazine.com/2014/08/13/congressional-candidate-seth-moulton-releases-first-tv-advertisement|accessdate=April 6, 2016|publisher=NoBo Magazine|date=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoulton is a member of the [[New Democrat Coalition]], a [[congressional caucus]] made up of Democrats who support an agenda described as \"moderate\", \"pro-growth\", and \"fiscally responsible\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref> Moulton was ranked the 34th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (as well as the most bipartisan member of Congress in either chamber from Massachusetts and the most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from [[New England]]) in the Bipartisan Index created by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] that ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf |title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index - House|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20Senate%20Scores.pdf |title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index - Senate|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Views on marijuana====\nMoulton has admitted using marijuana and supports legalization, saying, \"If you're not buying your marijuana from a dealer who sells heroin, who sells opioids, it's much less likely to be a gateway drug. The problem is now that it operates in the shadows. There's no control whatsoever. Someone goes and buys an edible, for example, there's no regulation about what's in that. It's like moonshine under Prohibition.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Kyle Scott |last=Clauss |title=Seth Moulton Says He Smoked Pot at Harvard, Supports Legalization|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/blog/2016/09/19/seth-moulton-smoked-pot-legalization|work=Boston Magazine|date=September 19, 2016|accessdate=October 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Foreign policy====\nMoulton opposed sending U.S. troops back to Iraq in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.necn.com/news/politics/Seth-Moultons-Bid-to-Unseat-US-Congressman-John-Tierney-271928791.html |title=Seth Moulton's Bid to Unseat US Congressman John Tierney| publisher=New England Cable News |date= August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Social issues====\nMoulton supports same-sex marriage and abortion rights.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin|title=Democrat Seth Moulton rejects support from same-sex marriage opponents |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/10/democrat-seth-moulton-rejects-support-from-same-sex-marriage-opponents/|accessdate=April 6, 2016|publisher=Metro Weekly|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zengerle|first1=Jason|title=This Massachusetts Race Will Restore Your Faith in Our Democracy|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120109/tisei-moulton-race-mass-rare-choice-two-great-candidates|accessdate=April 6, 2016|publisher=New Republic|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> He supports increased gun control.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schoenberg |first1=Shira |title=Sen. Elizabeth Warren, Rep. Seth Moulton voice support for President Obama's gun laws |url=http://www.masslive.com/politics/index.ssf/2016/01/sen_elizabeth_warren_rep_seth.html |accessdate=April 6, 2016|publisher=Mass Live|date=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Cybersecurity====\nIn September 2018, Moulton co-sponsored, together with [[Elise Stefanik]] and [[Dan Donovan (politician)|Dan Donovan]], the \"Cyber Ready Workforce Act\" advanced by [[Jacky Rosen]]. The legislation would create a grant program within the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] to \"create, implement and expand registered apprenticeships\" in [[cybersecurity]]. It aims to offer certifications and connect participants with businesses in order to \"boost the number\" workers for federal jobs in said trade.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Dem introduces bill to create federal cybersecurity apprenticeship program |url=https://thehill.com/policy/cybersecurity/406577-dem-introduces-bill-to-create-federal-cybersecurity-apprenticeship |website=The Hill |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Transportation policy====\nMoulton is the driving force behind the [[North\u2013South Rail Link|North-South Rail Link]], a project aimed at uniting Boston's north and south-side [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] lines, decongesting its subway lines, and linking the commuter rail to [[Logan International Airport]] via the Blue Line. He is an avid proponent of public transportation and frequently rides the commuter rail.<ref>{{cite news|title=Look to Texas Model for Boston rail link|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/massachusetts/2015/10/8579572/moulton-look-texas-model-boston-rail-link|publisher=Capital New York |date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Riding the rails with Moulton |url=http://www.salemnews.com/news/local_news/riding-the-rails-with-moulton/article_5b2ed628-392e-5021-9156-dd3bcc355e02.html|publisher=Salem News|date=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Economic policy====\nIn March 2016, with regard to the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]], Moulton said he needed to further analyze the proposal.<ref name=rise/>\n\n====Energy policy====\nMoulton supports the expansion of nuclear energy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wade |first=Christian M. |url=http://www.eagletribune.com/news/pilgrim-s-closure-revives-nuclear-energy-debate/article_c30f2e3f-30fb-5343-8145-66af9d51949d.html |title=Pilgrim's closure revives nuclear energy debate |work=[[The Eagle-Tribune]] |date=October 29, 2015 |accessdate=March 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n====Views on Donald Trump====\nIn a March 2016 interview with ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', Moulton compared the rise of the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican presidential front-runner]], [[Donald Trump]], with [[Adolf Hitler's rise to power]] in the 1930s. Moulton said that, in order to understand how an educated society \"can elect a demagogue,\" voters should read about how the German people elected Hitler in the early 20th century.<ref name=rise>{{cite news|last=Andersen|first=Travis|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/03/23/congressman-seth-moulton-compares-rise-donald-trump-election-hitler/5nbZpv2d4B25N2A3hgOldP/story.html|title=Moulton compares Trump's rise to election of Hitler in 1930s|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=March 24, 2016 |accessdate=March 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Gun policy====\nOn June 15, 2016, Moulton appeared on the cover of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' with the statement \"No Civilian Should Own This Gun\" in reference to [[semi-automatic firearm|semi-automatic]] [[assault weapons]]. The cover pictures Moulton during a deployment to [[Iraq]], carrying an issued [[M4 carbine]].<ref>{{cite news|title=No Civilian Should Own This Weapon |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nydn-front-pages-2016-gallery-1.2482879?pmSlide=1.2674384|accessdate=June 17, 2016|agency=New York Daily News|date=June 15, 2016}}</ref> The particular gun in the picture has never been legal for civilians to own due to the \"[[Firearm Owners Protection Act#Ban On New Automatic Firearms|Hughes Amendment]]\" in 1986.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=April 10, 2017|title=Firearm Owners Protection Act |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Firearm_Owners_Protection_Act&oldid=774788290|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref>\n\nMoulton penned an opinion piece promoting gun control, including the statement: \"There's simply no reason for a civilian to own a military-style assault weapon. It's no different than why we outlaw civilian ownership of rockets and landmines.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moulton|first1=Seth|title=Civilians have no reason for owning assault weapons, but Congress lacks the courage to stop them: Congressman and Iraq War vet|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/civilians-no-reason-owning-assault-weapons-article-1.2674107|accessdate=June 17, 2016|publisher=New York Daily News|date=June 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 23, 2017, Moulton announced on [[Twitter]] his engagement to his girlfriend, Liz Boardman, a senior client partner at an executive search firm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2017/06/23/congressman-seth-moulton-announces-engagement/guGu11Sqz80v0bKoIFgzgO/story.html|title=Congressman Seth Moulton announces engagement|last=Shanahan|first=Mark|date=June 23, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2017|publisher=Boston Globe}}</ref> They were married at the Old North Church, Marblehead, Mass., on September 22, 2017.<ref>Shanahan, Mark, BOSTON GLOBE, Sept., 22, 2017</ref> Moulton announced the birth of his first child with his wife Liz, a girl named Emmy, in October 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2018/10/12/seth-moulton-announces-birth-his-first-child/jegPlb0iqSwrvt3Dq3ovwL/story.html#comments|title=Seth Moulton announces birth of his first child - The Boston Globe|work=BostonGlobe.com|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{s-s